"Putting the record straight The dawning of the new year calls for clarity and is a time to dust out the old ways of thinking about security, say experts Dario Forte and Richard Power. They have identified nine false myths that have been associated with the field for some time. And they give much evidence to back up their arguments. They controversially dismiss the widely accepted idea that 80% of all attacks stem from insiders. Many attacks hail from technically competent external hackers who know exactly what they are doing. In addition Forte and Power dispute that cybercrime costs are exaggerated. They point out that this assertion is unfounded. There is no method for accurately measuring economic security losses in the industry, meaning that we are in the dark on the matter. They also point out that many organisations do not want to quantify their losses. And if they did calculate the costs of security breaches, they would keep the figures within corporate walls. But that is only the start of the nine false notions. Recently, we have been looking long and hard, in retrospect, not only at the year 2005, but at the last decade, so that we can understand the year 2006 better and be in a strong position to work alongside our colleagues in meeting the challenges of the decade ahead. Where are we? How far have we come? Where are we going? The answers to these questions are difficult to wrest from within the maelstrom: encouragement, disappointment, vindication, astonishment and despair swirl around the hard facts, and submerge them again and again, just beyond our reach. To provide some clarity, we have exhumed a list of “Nine False Notions About Cyber Security” that we drew up in 2000, at the turn of the century, mid-way throught the tumultuous decade that commenced in 1995."
